
struct folio :
        clarifying memory management with page folios.
        this structure based on the base page structure,which
        usually has the size same as the hardware's page size.
        This structure appears first time in kernel v5.16,by
        Jonathan Corbet since 2021.

        Every base page of memory managed by the kernel is
        represented by a page structure in the system memory map.
        When a compound page is created out of a set of base pages,
        the page structure for the first page in the set(head page)
        is specially marked(PG_head) to make its compound 
        nature explicit.The other information in that structure
        refers to the compound page as a whole.All of the other
        pages(tail pages) are marked(PG_tail) as such,with a pointer to
        the page structure for the associated head page.

        ! 64-bit : PG_head the head page and PG_tail the tail pages.
                   PageHead(), PageTail()
          32-bit : PG_compound all the pages in the compound page,
                   PG_reclaim all the taile pages in the compound page.
                   PageCompound()
                   # compound page can not be represented in the page cache,
                     thus that flag(PG_reclaim) can be reused for
                     compound page.

        struct page.@first_page: pointer to the head page of the compound
                                 page in which this tail page is contained.
        struct page.@ptl:        hold when the page has a Page Table Entries.
        struct page.@slab:       not NULL if the page is owned by a slab allocator.

        compound_head() : routine can be used to find out the head page associated
                          with tail page.
                          # this is an inline function,thus will enlarge kernel size.

        the first tail page :
          # compound page's meta information.
          @lru.prev => stores the order of the compound page
          @lru.next => stores the destructor for the compound page

          [0]         [1]
        +------------------------------------------------------+
        |           |                 |                  |     |
        | head page | first tail page | second tail page | ... |    => page descriptor array
        |           |                 |                  |     |
        +------------------------------------------------------+
          ^           | |   |
          |           | |   |
          |           | |   +--> @lru.next => destructor of compound page
          |           | +--> @lru.prev => order of compound page
          +-----------+ @first_page


        Ambiguity :
                If a function is passed a pointer to a page structure
                for a tail page,is it expected to act on that tail page
                or on the compound page as a whole?

                A function which has a struct page argument might
                be expecting a head or base page and will BUG if
                given a tail page of a compound page.
                It might work with any kind of page and operate
                on PAGE_SIZE bytes.
                It might work with any kind of page and operate
                on page_size() bytes if given a head page but
                PAGE_SIZE bytes if given a base or tail page.
                It might operate on page_size() bytes if passed
                a head or tail page.

                ! page_size(@page) => PAGE_SIZE << compound_order(@page)
                  if @page is a base page,then compound_order() will BUG,
                  because it assume @page is an array of pages in one
                  compound page.

        The folio type itself is defined as a simple wrapper structure :
                struct folio {
                        struct page page;
                };

                get_folio() => increase refcount of foilo
                put_folio() => decrease refcount of folio

        <linux/mm_types.h> /* kernel version 6.19.6 */
          /**
           * folio - represents a contiguous set of bytes.
           * # public:
           * @flags: identical to the page flags
           * @lru:   Least Recently Used list,tracks how recently this folio was used
           * @mlock_count:
           *         number of times this folio has been pinned by mlock()
           * @mapping:
           *         the file this page belongs to,or refers to the anon_vma for
           *         anonymous memory
           * @index: offset within the file,in units of pages.for anonymous memory,
           *         this is the index from the beginning of the mmap
           * @share: number of DAX mappings that reference this folio
           *         # dax_associate_entry
           * @private:
           *         filesystem per-folio data
           * @swap:  used for swp_entry_t if folio_test_swapcache()
           * @_mapcount:
           *         do not access this member directly,use folio_mapcount() to find out
           *         how many times this folio is mapped by userspace
           * @_refcount:
           *         do not access this member directly,use folio_ref_count() to find how
           *         many references there are to this folio
           * @memcg_data:
           *         memory cgroup data
           * @pgmap: metadata for ZONE_DEVICE mappings
           * @virtual:
           *         virtual address in the kernel direct map
           * @_last_cpupid:
           *         IDs of last CPU and last process that accessed the folio
           * @_entire_mapcount:
           *         do not use directly,call folio_entire_mapcount()
           * @_large_mapcount:
           *         do not use directly,call folio_mapcount()
           * @_nr_pages_mapped:
           *         do not use outside of rmap and debug code
           * @_pincount:
           *         do not use directly,call folio_maybe_dma_pinned()
           * @_nr_pages:
           *         do not use directly,call folio_nr_pages()
           * @_mm_id:
           *         do not use outside of rmap code
           * @_mm_ids:
           *         do not use outside of rmap code
           * @_mm_id_mapcount:
           *         do not use outside of rmap code
           * @_hugetlb_subpool:
           *         do not use directly,use accessor in hugetlb.h
           * @_hugetlb_cgroup:
           *         do not use directly,use accessor in hugetlb_cgroup.h
           * @_hugetlb_cgroup_rsvd:
           *         do not use directly,use accessor in hugetlb_cgroup.h
           * @_hugetlb_hwpoison:
           *         do not use directly,call raw_hwp_list_head()
           * @_deferred_list: 
           *         folios to be split under memory pressure
           * @_unused_slab_obj_exts:
           *         placeholder to match obj_exts in struct slab
           * # folio is a physically,virtually,and logically contiguous set of bytes.
           *   it is a power-of-two in size,and it is aligned to that same power-of-two.
           *   it is at least as large as %PAGE_SIZE.
           *   if it is in the page cache,it is at a file offset which is a multiple of
           *   that power-of-two.
           *   it may be mapped into userspace at an address which is at an arbitrary page
           *   offset,but its kernel virtual address is aligned to its size.
           * # some private members are not used currently.
           */
          struct folio {
                  /* private: do not document the anon union */
                  union {
                          struct {
                  /* public: */
                                  memdesc_flags_t flags;
                                  union {
                                          struct list_head lru;
                  /* private: avoid cluttering the output */
                                          /* For the Unevictable "LRU list" slot */
                                          struct {
                                                  /* Avoid compound_head */
                                                  void *__filler;
                  /* public: */
                                                  unsigned int mlock_count;
                  /* private: */
                                          };
                  /* public: */
                                          struct dev_pagemap *pgmap;
                                  };
                                  struct address_space *mapping;
                                  union {
                                          pgoff_t index;
                                          unsigned long share;
                                  };
                                  union {
                                          void *private;
                                          swp_entry_t swap;
                                  };
                                  atomic_t _mapcount;
                                  atomic_t _refcount;
          #ifdef CONFIG_MEMCG
                                  unsigned long memcg_data;
          #elif defined(CONFIG_SLAB_OBJ_EXT)
                                  unsigned long _unused_slab_obj_exts;
          #endif
          #if defined(WANT_PAGE_VIRTUAL)
                                  void *virtual;
          #endif
          #ifdef LAST_CPUPID_NOT_IN_PAGE_FLAGS
                                  int _last_cpupid;
          #endif
                  /* privte: the union with struct page is transitional */
                          };
                          struct page page;
                  };

                  union {
                          struct {
                                  unsigned long _flags_1;
                                  unsigned long _head_1;
                                  union {
                                          struct {
                  /* public: */
                                                  atomic_t _large_mapcount;
                                                  atomic_t _nr_pages_mapped;
          #ifdef CONFIG_64BIT
                                                  atomic_t _entire_mapcount;
                                                  atomic_t _pincount;
          #endif
                                                  mm_id_mapcount_t __mm_id_mapcount[2];
                                                  union {
                                                          mm_id_t _mm_id[2];
                                                          unsigned long _mm_ids;
                                                  };
                  /* private: the union with struct page is transitional */
                                          };
                                          unsigned long _usable_1[4];
                                  };
                                  atomic_t _mapcount_1;
                                  atomic_t _refcount_1;
                  /* public: */

          #ifdef NR_PAGES_IN_LARGE_FOLIO
                                  unsigned int _nr_pages;
          #endif
                  /* private: the union with struct page is transitional */
                          };
                          struct page __page_1;
                  };

                  union {
                          struct {
                                  unsigned long _flags_2;
                                  unsigned long _head_2;
                  /* public: */
                                  struct list_head _deferred_list;
          #ifndef CONFIG_64BIT
                                  atomic_t _entire_mapcount;
                                  atomic_t _pincount;
          #endif
                  /* private: the union with struct page is transitional */
                          };
                          struct page __page_2;
                  };

                  union {
                          struct {
                                  unsigned long _flags_3;
                                  unsigned long _head_3;
                  /* public: */
                                  void *_hugetlb_subpool;
                                  void *_hugetlb_cgroup;
                                  void *_hugetlb_cgroup_rsvd;
                                  void *_hugetlb_hwpoison;
                  /* private: the union with struct page is transitional */
                          };
                          struct page __page_3;
                  };
          };

        ! folio is used only for compound page,and routine folio_alloc() is used to
          allocate a folio.
          this function relies on __alloc_pages_noprof(),and which will return a 
          page descriptor.

          because sizeof(struct page) is larger than sizeof(struct folio),and all
          members of a folio is inclued in the unions.thus we can convert the head page
          descriptor to the folio descriptor.
          /**
           * the first union of folio at least is large enough to contain a 
           * struct page object,and the second,the third,the fourth are so on.
           * when we convert a head page descriptor to a folio page descriptor,actually,
           * we only used the first union.
           * when we decided to use folio to represents compound page,we will no longer
           * need the head page descriptor,use the folio as instead.
           * if we need to destroy the head page,we can easily convert the folio descriptor
           * to page descriptor,and destroy the memory this descriptor has ocuppied.
           *
           * ! size of struct page usually is 64 bytes.
           *   size of struct folio usually is 256 bytes.
           *                                   #^ @page @__page_1 @__page_2 @__page_3
           */

          macro function page_folio(@p) can return the folio which contains the tail page.
          macro function folio_page(@folio, @n) can return the tail page in @folio has
          index @n. /* the first head page has index 0 */

        Layout :
          +--------------------------------------------------------------+
          |                   |                 |                  |     |
          | folio (head page) | first tail page | second tail page | ... |
          |                   |                 |                  |     |
          +--------------------------------------------------------------+
            ^                   |
            |                   |
            +-------------------+ @compound_head
                                   bit 0 => 1 PageTail
                                   bit 1 -- 31 => head page descriptor

          the macor folio_page(@folio, @n) is expanded to
                  (&(folio)->page + (n))
          this is OK,because the structure folio is composed in several unions,
          so we can consider the struct folio is the struct page because
                  struct folio { <------------------------+
                          union {                         |
                                  struct page page; ------+
                          };
                  };
                  ! union's magic
          hence,we finally we get the right address of tail page.

io_uring subsystem :
        io_uring is a high-performance asynchrnous I/O support introduced in kernel 5.1,
        used as alternation of AIO.
        
        initialization :
          this subsystem is initialized during system booting phase,by the init function
                  static int __init io_uring_init(void); /* defined in <io_uring/io_uring.c> */
          this function first go to creates an object named @kmem_args is type of
          struct kmem_cache_args.
          next,invoke io_uring_optable_init() to initialize io_uring operation table.
          proceed to create kmem cache through kmem_cache_create(),the cache's name is
          "io_kiocb",object size is sizeof(struct io_kiocb).
          enabled slab flags are :
                  SLAB_HWCACHE_ALIGN
                  SLAB_PANIC
                  SLAB_ACCOUNT
                  SLAB_TYPESAFE_BY_RCU
          global pointer named @req_cachep is defined in the same file,which saves the address
          of the newly created kmem cache object.
          finally,invoke alloc_workqueue() to create a new workqueue "iou_exit",workqueue flag
          is WQ_UNBOUND(have not bound to any CPU),and the maximum number of in-flight work items
          is 64.
          the new workqueue object's address is saved in static pointer named @iou_wq,which is
          defined in the same file,and it is readonly after initialization.
          /* this init function will does a lot of BUG checkings.
           * if CONFIG_SYSCTL is enabled,it will invoke register_sysctl_init() to
           * register sysctl interface.
           */

          ! structure kmem_cache_args :
            <linux/slab.h>
              /**
               * kmem_cache_args - structure collects less common arguments for 
               *                   kmem_cache_create().
               * @align:           required alignment for the objects.
               * @useroffset:      usercopy region offset.
               * @usersize:        usercopy region size.
               *                   @useroffset = 0 is valid if @usersize is not _zero_.
               *                   @usersize = 0 means no usercopy region is specified.
               * @freeptr_offset:  custom offset for the free pointer in the
               *                   SLAB_TYPESAFE_BY_RCU caches.
               *                   by default,SLAB_TYPESAFE_BY_RCU caches place the free
               *                   pointer outside of the object,this might cause the object
               *                   to grow in size,through this member,cache creator has a
               *                   reason to avoid this,use this member to specify a custom
               *                   free pointer offset in their struct where the free pointer
               *                   will be placed.
               *                   this requries the caller to ensure the fields are required
               *                   to guard against object recycling must be valid.
               *                   # @freeptr_offset = 0 is valid.
               *                   # if @freeptr_offset is specified,@use_freeptr_offset must be
               *                     set to true.
               *                   # @ctor currently is not supported with custom free pointers
               *                     as a @ctor requires an external free pointer.
               * @use_freeptr_offset:
               *                   use custom free pointer offset indicator.
               * @ctor:            constructor for the objects,this @ctor is called for each object
               *                   in a newly allocated slab page.
               *                   # NULL => no constructor
               *                   ! it is the cache user's responsibility to free object in the same
               *                     state as after calling the constructor,or deal appropriately with
               *                     any differences between a freshly constructed and a reallocated
               *                     object.
               * @sheaf_capacity:  enable sheaves of given capacity for the cache.with a non-zero value,
               *                   allocations from the cache go through caching arrays called sheaves.
               *                   each CPU has a main sheaf that is always present,and a spare sheaf that
               *                   may be not present.when both are empty,there is an attempt to replace
               *                   _an_ empty sheaf with a full sheaf from the per-node barn.
               *                   if no full sheaf is available,and GFP flags allow blocking,a sheaf is
               *                   allocated and filled from slab(s) using bulk allocation.
               *                   otherwise,the allocation falls back to the normal operation allocating
               *                   a single object from a slab.
               *                   when freeing and both per-CPU sheaves are full,the barn may replace it with
               *                   an empty sheaf,unless it is over capacity.in that case,a sheaf is bulk freed
               *                   to slab pages.
               *                   # 0 => no sheaf
               *                   # allocations via kmem_cache_alloc_node() with a node specified other than
               *                     NUMA_NO_NODE will bypass sheaves.
               *                   # bulk allocation and free operations also try to use the per-CPU sheaves and
               *                     barn,but fallback to using slab pages directly.
               *                   # this member will be ignored if slub_debug is enabled for the cache.
               * # any uninitialized fields of the structure are interpreted as unused,but @freeptr_offset = 0 is
               *   valid,thus @use_freeptr_offset is the indicator.
               *   pass NULL kmem_cache_args object to kmem_cache_create() means all members are unused.
               */
              struct kmem_cache_args {
                      unsigned int align;
                      unsigned int useroffset;
                      unsigned int usersize;
                      unsigned int freeptr_offset;
                      bool use_freeptr_offset;
                      void (*ctor)(void *);
                      unsigned int sheaf_capacity;
              };

          ! io_uring used kmem_cache_args {
                    .useroffset = offsetof(struct io_kiocb, cmd.data),
                    .usersize = sizeof_field(struct io_kiocb, cmd.data),
                    .freeptr_offset = offsetof(struct io_kiocb, work),
                    .use_freeptr_offset = true,
            }

          function io_uring_optable_init() is defined in <io_uring/opdef.c>.
                  void __init io_uring_optable_init(void);
          for each element in the array named @io_issue_defs,it checks
          the @prep member of the element is type of struct io_issue_def.
          if it is not equal to io_eopnotsupp_prep(),proceed checks whether
          current element's @issue member is NULL,if it is the case,that means
          there is a BUG.   /* operation is supported,but can not issue,BUG */

          ! @io_issue_defs is defined in <io_uring/opdef.c>,which is an array of
            const struct io_issue_def.it collects a lot of io_uring supporting
            informations to kernel I/O infrastructures.such readv,writev,fsync,etc.

          ! structure io_issue_def :
              <io_uring/opdef.h>
                /**
                 * io_issue_def - structure used to describes how kernel supports with
                 *                the specified kind of io_uring issue,and some requirements.
                 * @needs_file:   needs req->file assigned
                 * @plug:         should block plug
                 * @ioprio:       supports prioritied I/O
                 * @iopoll:       supports I/O poll
                 * @buffer_select:
                 *                operation supports buffer selection
                 * @hash_reg_file:
                 *                hash workqueue insertion if file is a regular file
                 * @unbound_nonreg_file:
                 *                unbound workqueue insertion if file is a non-regular file
                 * @pollin:       set if opcode supports polled "wait" - input
                 * @pollout:      set if opcode supports polled "wait" - output
                 * @poll_exclusive:
                 *                set if opcode supports polled "wait" - exclusive poll
                 * @audit_skip:   skip auditing
                 * @iopoll_queue: have to be put into the iopoll list
                 * @vectored:     vectored opcode,set if vectored and handler needs to know
                 * @is_128:       set to 1 if this opcode uses 128-bit sqes in a mixed sq
                 * @async_size:   size of async data needed,if any
                 * @issue:        method used to issue submission
                 * @prep:         method used to prepare submission
                 * ! ->issue will be called by __io_issue_sqe(),and which is usually called by
                 *   io_issue_sqe().
                 *   ->prep will be called by io_init_req(),and which is called by io_submit_sqe().
                 */
                struct io_issue_def {
                        unsigned needs_file:1;
                        unsigned plug:1;
                        unsigned ioprio:1;
                        unsigned iopoll:1;
                        unsigned buffer_select:1;
                        unsigned hash_reg_file:1;
                        unsigned unbound_nonreg_file:1;
                        unsigned pollin:1;
                        unsigned pollout:1;
                        unsigned poll_exclusive:1;
                        unsigned audit_skip:1;
                        unsigned iopoll_queue:1;
                        unsigned vectored:1;
                        unsigned is_128:1;

                        unsigned short async_size;        

                        int (*issue)(struct io_kiocb *, unsigned int);
                        int (*prep)(struct io_kiocb *, const struct io_uring_sqe *);                
                };

        system calls :
          same as AIO,we need to issue request to kernel for use io_uring,if the request has
          been satisfied,then kernel will exports the completion state.
          in 6.19.6,there is only three system calls about io_uring: io_uring_setup,io_uring_enter,
          io_uring_register.

          <io_uring/io_uring.c>
            /**
             * sys_io_uring_setup - prepare io_uring.
             * @entries:            the number of submissions can be contained in the
             *                      submission queue.
             * @params:             io_uring parameter from userspace
             * return:              file descriptor OR error code
             * # this routine first needs to check io_uring_allowed(),if io_uring is disabled,or
             *   we have no capability to make use of io_uring,-EPERM will be returned.if we are
             *   permitted to use io_uring,then io_uring_allowed() will does the last 
             *   security checking via LSM.
             *   ! io_uring_allowed() returns -EPERM
             *             if @sysctl_io_uring_disabled == 2.
             *                                             (2 => fully disabled, 1 => half disabled and restricted)
             *             if make_kgid() from @sysctl_io_uring_group in @init_user_ns returned a
             *             invalid kgid.
             *             if make_kgid() returned kgid is not in @io_uring_group.
             *     if io_uring is not disabled OR we have capability CAP_SYS_ADMIN,then we can use it.
             */
            SYSCALL_DEFINE2(io_uring_setup, u32, entries, struct io_uring_params __user *, params)
            => asmlinkage long sys_io_uring_setup(u32 entries, struct io_uring_params __user *params);

            /**
             * io_uring_setup - kernel routine used to setup io_uring.
             * @entries:        maximum number of submissions can be contained in submission queue.
             * @params:         userspace io_uring parameters.
             * return:          file descriptor to the io_uring OR error code
             */
            static long io_uring_setup(u32 entries, struct io_uring_params __user *params);

            description for io_uring_setup() :
              this function setup an aio uring context,and returns the fd.
                                    #^asynchronous I/O,the old AIo still functions,and which need kioctx.
              structure io_ctx_config is used to describes(configures) io_uring context.
              /**
               * <io_uring/io_uring.h>
               * # io_uring aio context config
               * struct io_ctx_config {
               *         struct io_uring_params p; // used to store io_uring parameter from userspace
               *         struct io_rings_layout layout; // ring layout
               *         struct io_uring_params __user *uptr; // stores the userspace pointer of io_uring parameters
               * };
               */
              this routine setup the context @config {
                      copy @params to .p
                      set .p.sq_entries to @entries
                      set .uptr to @params
                      .layout is memset to _zero_
              }
              if we failed to copy from user,or @config.p.resv is not _zero_ fully filled,return -EFAULT.
              .resv is an array of __u32,size is 3.
              finally,invoke io_uring_create(),pass it address of @config,return the return value to caller.

            /**
             * io_uring_create - create io_uring from given config.
             * @config:          the config.
             * return:           file descriptor to the io_uring OR error code
             */
            static __cold int io_uring_create(struct io_ctx_config *config);
            
            description for io_uring_create() :
              the main works this routine has to done :
                prepare config via io_prepare_config(),the primary processing is to
                setup @config->p.

                allocate io_ring_ctx via io_ring_ctx_alloc(),this function will create
                a new io_uring context.(@ctx)

                setup the context,that is set @clockid to CLOCK_MONOTONIC,and set
                @clock_offset to _zero_.                 #^we will pick timepoint from this clock.

                set @ctx->user to current_user(),if current user has no superior,this is determined
                by ns_capable_noaudit(&@init_user_ns, CAP_IPC_LOCK).

                adjust some members in the context based on context(@ctx) flags {
                        !IORING_SETUP_NO_SQARRAY -> static_branch_deferred_inc()

                        IORING_SETUP_DEFER_TASKRUN AND !IORING_SETUP_IOPOLL AND
                        !IORING_SETUP_SQPOLL -> @ctx->task_complete = true

                        IORING_SETUP_IOPOLL AND !IORING_SETUP_SQPOLL -> @ctx->syscall_iopoll = 1

                        IORING_SETUP_SQPOLL OR IORING_SETUP_COOP_TASKRUN -> @ctx->notify_method = TWA_SIGNAL_NO_IPI
                        else: @ctx->notify_method = TWA_SIGNAL                        
                }

                adjust some members in the context based on other members {
                        !@ctx->task_complete -> @ctx->poll_activated = true
                }

                memory grab @current->mm,pin current task's mm_struct,and set @ctx->mm_account to @current->mm.

                invoke io_allocate_scq_urings(),this function allocate submission ring and completion ring for
                this io_uring context @ctx.it relies on io_create_region(),and which will allocate pages for
                the ring,or pin the exist pages rather than allocte new pages if IORING_MEM_REGION_TYPE_USER is
                set.at the end,io_create_region() invoke io_region_init_ptr() on the given io_mapped_region
                descriptor,to vmap() the pages from an page array to virtually contiguous memory region.
                for submission ring,the io_mapped_region descriptor is @ctx->ring_region,for completion ring,
                the descriptor is @ctx->sq_region.
                @ctx->rings is the pointer points to .ring_region->ptr,it is the startup address of cq ring.
                @ctx->sq_sqes is the pointer points to .sq_region->ptr,it is the startup address of sq ring.
                /* sq and cq has different mmap offset.
                 * sq mmap offset: IORING_OFF_SQES
                 * cq mmap offset: IORING_OFF_CQ_RING
                 */

                invoke io_sq_offload_create() to get io_sq_data,create a new io thread
                through create_io_thread(),this new task is copied from current process.
                                           /* the new task will executes io_sq_thread() function.
                                            * the thread period invoke io_submit_sqes().
                                            * if nothing to does or current sqes have been submitted,
                                            * it will enter TASK_INTERRUPTIBLE,and wait on ->sq_data->wait.
                                            * ! the sq_data object's address is passed to create_io_thread()
                                            *   by io_sq_offload_create().
                                            * ! the newly created thread is inactive,io_sq_offload_create()
                                            *   activate it before return.
                                            */
                the new task is not kernel thread,it is io_uring worker,and it is user worker.
                next,invoke io_uring_alloc_task_context() on current io_uring context and this
                new task,to create a new io_uring_task for this io_uring.
                /* this new task's @io_uring member is set to this io_uring_task */

                copy_to_user() the @config->p to @config->uptr.
                /* prepare config has setup ->p,thus we need tell user the detail. */

                invoke io_uring_get_file() on the io_uring context to attach
                a file object.the file_operations is @io_uring_fops {
                                      .release = io_uring_release,

                                      /**
                                       * mmap() method is very important,because of it,we can let userspace
                                       * application mmap the rings and submission array.
                                       */
